Understanding JavaScript String Methods and Polyfills

JavaScript strings are one of the most common data types. 
Knowing how to manipulate strings efficiently is crucial, not only for coding tasks but also for interviews.

What String Methods Are
String methods are built-in functions that let you manipulate, query, or transform strings.
Examples include:
length → property to get string length
toUpperCase() → converts to uppercase
slice() → extracts part of a string
split() → breaks a string into an array
replace() → replaces parts of a string

const text = "Hello World";
console.log(text.toUpperCase()); // "HELLO WORLD"
console.log(text.slice(0, 5));   // "Hello"

🔹 Why Developers Write Polyfills
A polyfill is a custom implementation of a built-in method for older browsers or environments that don’t support it.
Writing polyfills helps:
Understand how a method works internally
Ensure compatibility


Example: Array.prototype.includes Polyfill

if (!String.prototype.includes) {
    String.prototype.includes = function(substring) {
        return this.indexOf(substring) !== -1;
    };
}

console.log("Hello World".includes("World")); // true


🔹 Implementing Simple String Utilities
1️⃣ Reverse a String


function reverseString(str) {
    let reversed = "";
    for (let i = str.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        reversed += str[i];
    }
    return reversed;
}

console.log(reverseString("JavaScript")); // "tpircSavaJ"

2️⃣ Capitalize First Letter
function capitalize(str) {
    if (!str) return "";
    return str[0].toUpperCase() + str.slice(1);
}

console.log(capitalize("hello")); // "Hello"

Palindrome Check

function isPalindrome(str) {
    const reversed = str.split("").reverse().join("");
    return str === reversed;
}

console.log(isPalindrome("level")); // true

🔹 Importance of Understanding Built-in Behavior
Debugging → Know how your method works if it behaves unexpectedly
Performance → Built-in methods are usually optimized
Cross-browser coding → Some environments may not support newer methods


